                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d15">
                <head>15. National Security Action Memorandum No. 76<note n="0" type="source"
                        xml:id="d15fn0">Source: Department of State, NSAMs: Lot 72 D 316, No
                        classification marking. Another copy bears the date August 20.
                        (Ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-08-21">August 21, 1961</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>MEMORANDUM FOR</head>
                    <item>Under Secretary of State <persName>George Ball</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>I am concerned about what will be the economic effect upon the United States if
                    England joins the common market. I believe we should have a realistic detailed
                    study made by State. Treasury and the Council of Economic Advisers. I have been
                    informed that the effect will be extremely serious. Could you consider the
                    matter and talk to me about it and suggest what action we should properly take.
                    We have been in the position, of course, of encouraging the expansion of the
                    common market for political reasons. If it should have an extremely adverse
                    effect upon us a good deal of responsibility would be laid upon our
                    doorstep.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">JFK</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
